issue_body:
Running a query with `TBUCKET(100)` fails with a wrong verification exception when the query filters don't contain any data. Running the same query with e.g. `TBUCKET(10s)` succeeds:

<img width="1392" height="918" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/e2fea7b0-daf4-4f7c-9700-ad110b0830d0" />

```
[esql] > Unexpected error from Elasticsearch:
verification _exception - Found 1 problem line 1:46: numeric bucket count in [TBUCKET (100)] requires [from] and [to] parameters or a `@timestamp` range in the query range
```

Same range, but `TBUCKET(10s)` correctly shows empty data rather than failing the request:

<img width="1367" height="652" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d9dc1510-d641-4711-a3a6-fdfcb719c52d" />

Unfortunately it seems like the `numeric bucket count in [TBUCKET(10)] requires [from] and [to] parameters or a @timestamp range in the query filter` verification exception in general seems to shadow verification problems: In `EsqlSession#analyzeWithRetry` we retry the analysis without a time filter if the first attempt of the original request fails. This causes the request to always fail with that message, independent of the actual root cause.

The following reporducer can be added to `RestEsqlTestCase`:

```

    public void testTopLevelFilterAllowsNumericTBucketWithoutExplicitBounds() throws IOException {
        indexTimestampData(3);

        RequestObjectBuilder builder = requestObjectBuilder().filter(b -> {
            b.startObject("range");
            {
                b.startObject("@timestamp").field("gte", "2020-12-13").field("lt", "2020-12-14").endObject();
            }
            b.endObject();
        }).query(fromIndex() + " | STATS count = COUNT(*) BY bucket = TBUCKET(10) | SORT bucket");

        Map<String, Object> result = runEsql(builder);
        assertResultMap(
            result,
            matchesList().item(matchesMap().entry("name", "count").entry("type", "long"))
                .item(matchesMap().entry("name", "bucket").entry("type", "date")),
            List.of()
        );
    }
```

If you change the query from `TBUCKET(10)` to `TBUCKET(10s)` the test passes.

